      <h1>How to Sell an Inherited House in Wichita, KS — Without the Headache</h1>

      <p>Inheriting a house in Wichita can feel like a gift and a burden at the same time. You're grieving, sorting through a lifetime of belongings, and now there's a house to deal with. The last thing you need is a six-month listing process.</p>

      <h2>Do You Have to Go Through Probate?</h2>
      <p>In most cases in Kansas, yes. If the deceased didn't set up a trust or transfer-on-death deed, the property will go through Sedgwick County probate court before it can be sold. A straightforward estate can move through in 4-6 months.</p>
      <p>Important: you can have a purchase agreement in place before probate closes. Cash buyers like Jacob can work with your timeline and wait for probate to finalize.</p>

      <h2>Your Three Main Options</h2>
      <p><strong>1. List With a Realtor.</strong> If the house is in good shape and you're not in a hurry, this can get you the highest price. But factor in commissions, repairs, and carrying costs.</p>
      <p><strong>2. Sell Yourself (FSBO).</strong> Saves commission but is a lot of work — especially with the title complications that often come with inherited properties.</p>
      <p><strong>3. Sell to a Cash Home Buyer.</strong> No repairs. No cleaning. No showings. Get an offer in 24 hours and close when probate clears.</p>

      <h2>Common Situations We See</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Out-of-state heirs who can't manage a Wichita property remotely</li>
        <li>Multiple siblings who want to divide the asset cleanly</li>
        <li>Estates with back taxes or liens</li>
        <li>Vacant homes accumulating costs</li>
        <li>Homes that need major repairs the heirs can't fund</li>
      </ul>

